What are the different phases of the component lifecycle?

Initialization:During this phase by setting up the default props and initial state for the upcoming tough journey.
Mounting: Mounting refers to putting the elements into the browser DOM. The key lifecycle methods in this phase are:
constructor() ‚Üí Initializes state and binds methods.
render() ‚Üí Returns JSX (UI of the component).
componentDidMount() ‚Üí Runs after the component is added to the DOM. Used for API calls, subscriptions, etc.


Updating: In this phase, a component will be updated when there is a change in the state or props of a component.
static getDerivedStateFromProps(props, state) ‚Üí Same as in mounting, updates state before re-render.
shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState) ‚Üí Determines whether the component should re-render or not (optimization).
render() ‚Üí Updates the UI based on new state or props

Unmounting: In this last phase of the component lifecycle, the component will be removed from the DOM.
componentWillUnmount() ‚Üí Used for cleanup, like removing event listeners, aborting API calls, etc.

ErrorHandling
static getDerivedStateFromError(error) ‚Üí Updates the state when an error occurs.
