What are fragments?
A Fragment in React is a lightweight wrapper that allows you to group multiple elements without adding extra nodes to the DOM.
By default, React components must return a single parent element. If you try to return multiple elements without wrapping them, you‚Äôll get an error

5Ô∏è‚É£ When to Use Fragments?
‚úî When returning multiple elements inside a component.
‚úî When avoiding extra <div> wrappers that clutter the DOM.
‚úî When rendering lists with .map() and needing a key prop.
**********************************************************************************************************************************
What are stateless components?


A stateless component (also called a functional component) is a component that:
‚úî Does not have its own state (useState)
‚úî Does not use lifecycle methods (useEffect, componentDidMount, etc.)
‚úî Only depends on props to render UI

Example of a Stateless Component
‚úÖ Functional (Stateless) Component
function Greeting(props) {
  return <h1>Hello, {props.name}!</h1>;
}

// Usage
<Greeting name="Ashish" />

3Ô∏è‚É£ When to Use Stateless Components?
‚úî When the component only renders UI
‚úî When using props to display dynamic content
‚úî When you want better performance & reusability
******************************************************************************************************************
what is Stateful Component


A stateful component is a React component that manages its own state using either:
‚úî Class component with this.state
‚úî Functional component with useState or other state management hooks
***************************************************************************************************************
How to Apply Validation on Props in React? üöÄ
In React, you can validate props using PropTypes, which helps catch errors and improve code maintainability.
npm install prop-types

Use PropTypes in your component to specify the expected data types for props.

import React from "react";
import PropTypes from "prop-types"; // Import PropTypes

function UserProfile({ name, age, isAdmin }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Name: {name}</h2>
      <p>Age: {age}</p>
      <p>Admin: {isAdmin ? "Yes" : "No"}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// ‚úÖ Applying prop validation
UserProfile.propTypes = {
  name: PropTypes.string.isRequired,  // Required string
  age: PropTypes.number,              // Optional number
  isAdmin: PropTypes.bool             // Boolean
};

// Default props (optional)
UserProfile.defaultProps = {
  age: 18,
  isAdmin: false
};

export default UserProfile;
